items.Title: Media City UK
items.Contractor: Bovis Lend Lease, Prater and 5m (UK) Ltd.
items.Copy:
The Peel Group had a vision to create a city within a city without the constraints of existing architecture or infrastructure. Over the past three years that vision has become MediaCityUK. MediaCityUK is designed specifically around the media industry. It’s a concept that reflects the way the industry is moving, as the boundaries between ‘new’ and ‘old’ media become increasingly blurred. It is also one of Europe’s biggest building projects with phase 1 covering more than 36 acres. Since the construction team arrived at Salford Quays in summer 2007 more than 7.3 million man hours have been spent on site. Work was completed in 2011 following input from nearly 2,000 people. Such a big development has had a massive effect on the local skyline, but together with the management contractor, Bovis Lend Lease, the Peel Group has also helped the community feel the economic benefits of the build process. To date, more than £200m of work has been awarded to Manchester contractors, including £92m to Salford- based firms.

As part of the construction of MediaCityUK there were a large number of new roofs that required waterproofing. Sika Liquid Plastics had the opportunity to create specifications for several of the projects within the development and successfully won buildings B and C (which are now used by the BBC), and the studios and residential towers.

As with any major new construction there were many challenges faced by the roofing contractors, such as working around other trades and ensuring new roofs are waterproofed on schedule.

Sika Liquid Plastics produces a range of complete roof systems, and several options were utilised on MediaCityUK. Building C levels 6 and 7 have an inverted roof system with level 7 also having a Decothane Delta 25 warm roof system installed on the upstands. In addition the timber canopy on this level was waterproofed with Decothane Delta 25. Building B and the studios had an Inverted Roof System installed which includes a root resistant version of Decothane – Liquid Plastics market leading liquid applied roofing membrane.

Finally the residential towers had a Cold Fusion Bonded Built-Up Roof System with a tapered insulation scheme and a Decothane Delta 25 waterproofing membrane.

Decothane is a liquid applied membrane that cures to provide completely seamless waterproof protection. It can easily accommodate any complex detail areas on the roof to provide total encapsulation and no risk of leaks. Because it is cold applied, the roofing contractors can work safely alongside other trades without causing any danger due to hot works. The Inverted Roof System is guaranteed to last for 25 years with a BBA durability statement that suggests it may last the lifetime of the building. Furthermore, because the systems were installed by Sika Liquid Plastics’ Quality Assured Contractors, a Single Point Guarantee could be issued covering materials and labour for complete peace of mind.

Throughout the project Sika Liquid Plastics’ Technical Field Services and Technical Customer Services Teams were on hand to provide comprehensive support. This began at the pre-start stage with attendance at design meetings. This helped our team develop a bespoke specification including detail drawings and any necessary calculations. During the works the local Technical Field Manager attended site regularly to provide inspection reports for the client and to sign off completed roof areas as each stage was completed. As a result the client knew when a roof could be handed over to other trades and the progress of the works could be closely monitored to ensure schedules and quality of work was maintained.

items.Title: Manchester Airport Terminal 1
items.Copy:
Manchester airport is one of the world’s principal airports and as such handles approximately 20 million passengers every year. Terminal 1 consists of 107 check-in desks, 24 pier served aircraft stands, 18 air bridges, restaurants and a shopping mall. When re-roofing a project of this magnitude, everything has to be carried out without interference to the smooth operation of the Airport’s commerce and functionality.

There were two phases of works required at Terminal 1, the first being a series of asphalt roofs that had failed. The main problem here was the presence of a great deal of plant equipment, which meant that the only system that could successfully waterproof the area would be a liquid applied system. Furthermore the majority of roof areas are regularly trafficked by workmen, therefore once the waterproofing was complete it needed to be overlaid with paving stones to create safe walkways.

A Decothane Omega 15 system from Liquid Plastics was specified and applied by a member of its Quality Assured Contractor programme - Weatherproofing Advisors. Prior to the waterproofing being applied, the existing paving stones were lifted and the underlying asphalt surfaces were power washed to ensure a clean substrate was available. Similar preparation was also carried out on roof areas with loose laid insulation being re-used once the new waterproofing system had been installed. For phase two

items.Title: Ronald McDonald House
items.Copy:
The Ronald McDonald House at Manchester Children’s hospital, provides free ‘home away from home’ accommodation, 365 days a year, to enable families to stay close to their child and maintain a degree of normal family life during the very stressful time when a child is seriously ill. Phase One is a 5 storey, 60 room house, allowing up to 240 people to stay at any one time. There is planning consent in place for a further 35 rooms in the future if demand dictates and funding allows. The ensuite rooms are supported with communal kitchen/living/dining areas on each floor, as well as play rooms, day rooms and extensive gardens at ground level and a rooftop terrace at first floor. It cost £7m to build and opened its doors to families at the end of May 2012.

Decothane Delta 25 from Sika Liquid Plastics was specified for the project and used in several different roof build-ups including an inverted roof in the plant area and a warm roof with a tapered insulation scheme on the main roof.

Decothane is a completely cold applied roofing membrane that cures to provide seamless waterproof protection, guaranteed for 25 years. Its liquid application makes it easy to apply to detail areas such as the projecting canopies. A root resistant version of Decothane is used in inverted roofs that is proven to resist penetration by even aggressive roots, and can be expected to last beyond the guaranteed 25 years due to its protected location at the bottom of the roof build-up.

The Decothane systems were chosen because of the ability to seamlessly waterproof complex details and the continuity of supplier for all of the waterproofing across the whole site. The cold application also meant safer working practices and allowed other trades to work in close proximity without any risk of danger.
